 BITTY BOX /bit'ee boks/ n. 1. A computer sufficiently small, primitive or
incapable as to cause a hacker acute claustrophobia at the thought of
developing for it. Especially used of small, obsolescent, single-tasking-only
personal machines like the Atari 800, Osborne, Sinclair, VIC-20, or TRS-80.
2. More generally, the opposite of `real computer' (see GET A REAL COMPUTER).
Pejorative. see also MESS-DOS, TOASTER, and TOY.